ect here is the "world-alien" (Weltfremdheit) in man that was formerly institutionalized in religions, but is increasingly dealt with in modern times through practices of psychotherapy. Originally written in 1993, this almost clairvoyant work examines how humans seek escape from the world in cross-cultural and historical context, up to the mania and world-escapism of our cybernetic network culture. Chapters delve into artificial habitats and forms of intoxication, from early Christian desert monks to pharmaco-theology through psychedelics. In classic form, Sloterdijk recalibrates and reinvents concepts from the ancient Greeks to Heidegger to develop an astonishingly contemporary philosophical anthropology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aMetaphysics. 0aOntology. 0aPhilosophical anthropology. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Phenomenology.2bisacsh  aalienation.  aaltered states.  adepth psychology.  aescapism.  aexistential phenomenology.  agnosticism.  ahistory of metaphysics.  ahistory of practices.  amania.1 aDansereau, Corey A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZimmermann, Gill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363901040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503639010423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503639010/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles